Sexing Notes: Beginnings of testes developing. Noticed a small amount of what looked like orange fungus around the genital area and on anus – only seen this before in Common Treeshrews.
Other Notes: Wasn't sure at first whether this was SS or DTT, because the tail appears to be all one colour and not the usual Maxomys white below, dark above. However on close inspection it did seem very slightly paler below, and this is a sub-adult so maybe the colouration will become more stark with time. Spent a while peering at him and I'm fairly certain it is an SS because (a) the large number and thickness of spines on uppers – like toothbrush bristles (b) overall colouration  (c) jizz of the face – small eyes, long and many vibrissae (d) no tuft at end of tail (e) no guard hairs on uppers. Have photos if you want to double check. Also just thought, occasionally have seen LTGs with Maxomys-like tails (e.g. 29/04/2014 Trap 34A) so maybe the variation sometimes works the opposite way round in Maxomys spp.

Well! I was quite surprised to see a recap LTG as I knew we hadn't caught any in either E100-1 or E100-2 and he had a fur clip so must be recent. As it turns out, this intrepid little explorer was first trapped in E10-1, Trap Station 7A on 24/04/2014 and then once more in the same grid at Trap Station 10B on 28/04/2014! Sexing Notes: Very small AGD. Have looked at M vs F AGD measurements for all SA and A WH trapped in E and in general females tend to be smaller than 9, with a few between 10-12.35, whereas males tend to be between 13-22, although with some between 9-12 and one SA at 8.5. I'm not sure how much AGD changes with age; if it's not by much then I would guess this individual is a female but if AGD is very variable according to age then it's not possible to say either way at the moment as there were no distinguishing features like mammae, start of balls/epididymal pouch, or an area/line where a 'hole' (sorry, crude) might develop.

Horse-Tailed Squirrel! Didn't have species code for this so have used HTSQ for now. Fairly sure on ID – head and shoulders grey, uppers grizzled brown with red tinge towards rump, unders pale/buff, tail long and clearly banded grey/black. The only issue I have is that the tail was very distinctively banded whereas the book doesn't mention this at all (its thoroughly helpful description is as follows: “Tail thick and bushy, but not very similar to that of a horse” …). However the only other possibilities based on colouration and size are Prevosts subspecies, but these all have red unders, or Giant, but this is overall too big and even if juvenile the HF of this individual was too small for Giant range (52.1 vs 67-86). Have photos.
